<h2 class="pageTitle"><span>Installing Python 2.x On Your Home Computer</span></h2>

</div>
<div class="contentMain">


<div id="pageContent"><h3><strong>Installing Python 2.x On Your Home Computer</strong></h3>
<p><strong>Windows XP</strong> and Vista and Windows 7</p>
<p>Download and Install Python 2.7.1:</p>
<blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Go to www.python.org/download/releases/2.7.1</li>
<li>Scroll down and pick Windows x86 MSI Installer (2.7.1).&nbsp; Do NOT install the 64 bit version;&nbsp; the 64 bit version conflicts with PIL, a library used in CS 111.</li>
<li>Save the installer. When it is downloaded, run it.</li>
<li>On the first installer screen select "install for all users". Click next.</li>
<li>Select where you want python to be installed. If the default is fine, click next.</li>
<li>In the Customization screen, click on the python drop down box at the top of the tree, and select "Entire feature will be installed on local hard-drive". Click next.</li>
<li>Click finish.</li>
</ol>
</blockquote>
<p>To test your installation:</p>
<blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Click start -&gt; programs</li>
<li>Click Python 2.7 -&gt; IDLE. A python shell should open up</li>
<li>At the prompt type "print 'hello world'"</li>
<li>"hello world" should be echoed back.</li>
</ol>
</blockquote>
<p>Add python to your path:</p>
<blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Right click on my computer, and pull down to properties.</li>
<li>Skip this step if you are not running Windows XP. Click on "Advanced system settings" on the left "Tasks" bar.</li>
<li>Click on Advanced.</li>
<li>Click on Environment Variables</li>
<li>In the "system variables" list, select "Path", and click on Edit.</li>
<li>Add ";c:\Python27" to the end of the "Variable value:" field. Note: DO NOT ADD the double quotes</li>
<li>Click "ok" three times.</li>
</ol>
</blockquote>
<p>To test the path:</p>
<blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Click Start/All Programs/Accessories/Command Prompt.</li>
<li>Type "python" without the double quotes.</li>
<li>You should see a python prompt; try entering "1+1", if you get "2" then everything is running correctly.</li>
</ol>
</blockquote>
<p>If you are looking for a windows editor that has more functionality than notepad and still saves files as text only, you might want to try <a target="_blank" href="http://www.contexteditor.org/">ConTEXT</a>or <a href="http://ftp.gnu.org/gnu/emacs/windows/emacs-22.3-bin-i386.zip">emacs</a>.<strong><br /></strong></p>
<p><strong>Mac OS</strong></p>
<p>Most modern Mac operating systems come with python preinstalled.</p>
<p>To access the terminal:</p>
<blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Go to Applications -&gt;Utilities.</li>
<li>Terminal should be in that list.</li>
<li>If you want permanent access to the terminal just drag it to the dock.</li>
</ol>
</blockquote>
<p>To test your installation of python:</p>
<blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Open a terminal.</li>
<li>Type python</li>
<li>A prompt should show up that looks like "&gt;&gt;&gt;"</li>
</ol>
</blockquote>
<p>If you are looking for a text editor, there is a lot of personal preference involved, two freeware versions for the mac are <a title="TextWrangler" target="_blank" href="http://www.barebones.com/products/TextWrangler/">TextWrangler</a> and <a title="SubEthaEdit" target="_blank" href="http://www.codingmonkeys.de/subethaedit/">SubEthaEdit</a>. If you don't want to download a new editor, a standard simple text editor that comes with most Macs is TextEdit.</p>
<p>To use TextEdit as your default editor:</p>
<blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Open TextEdit (in your applications folder)</li>
<li>Click TextEdit -&gt; Preferences</li>
<li>Change the format to plaintext</li>
<li>Click on the tabe marked "Open and Save"</li>
<li>Uncheck the box "Add .txt to plain text files"</li>
<li>Open a new document and you should be ready to go, just make sure when you save to save as "<em>YourProgramName</em>.py"</li>
</ol>
</blockquote>
<p>Linux</p>
<p>Most versions of linux come with python already installed. If yours doesn't or if you just can't find it, contact Mike Tie (mtie@carleton.edu).</p>
<p>You will have lots of choices of editors under linux, a simple one that we have had good luck with is <a title="http://www.nedit.org/" target="_blank" href="http://www.nedit.org/">NEdit</a>.</p>
<p>Problems:</p>
<p>If you run into trouble, please contact Mike Tie (mtie@carleton.edu).</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p></div>

</div>
